<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911226-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>911226-0036.</DOCID><HL>   Inside Track:   Symantec Director Sold Shares   For $34.6 Million in November   ----   By Alexandra Peers   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>12/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><CO>   SYMC</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>SOFTWARE (SOF)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>INSIDER TRADING (ISD)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- The biggest individual seller listed in thisweek's Insider Trading Spotlight is Peter Norton, a directorof Symantec Corp.   Mr. Norton sold $34.6 million of stock in the Cupertino,Calif., software company between Nov. 1 and Nov. 14,according to &quot;insider&quot; filings with the Securities andExchange Commission. The 1.18 million shares that Mr. Nortonsold represented 33% of his total direct and indirect stakein Symantec, the filings show.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Norton declined to comment on the sales, whichtogether represented one of the largest stock sales reportedto the SEC this year by corporate officers, directors andother insiders.   He is the founder of Peter Norton Computing Inc., thecompany that invented the much-used housekeeping program forpersonal computers, Norton Utilities, and Norton Anti-virus,a successful program introduced this year that detectscomputer viruses and repairs the damage they cause. Symantecacquired Peter Norton Computing in a $70 million transactionin August of last year.   Symantec stock, which traded in the $13- to $15-a-sharerange in January, has been on a steep climb for much of 1991.It was quoted at $39.50 in national over-the-counter trading.Mr. Norton sold his shares at an average price of $29.30each, SEC filings show.   For the fiscal second quarter ended Sept. 30, Symantecposted earnings of $2.4 million, or 10 cents a share,reversing a year-earlier loss.</TEXT></DOC>